ABSTRACT: Three new arthrichitin derivatives I-K (1-3) and three known congeners
were isolated from a coculture of
mangrove-derived fungi Aspergillus sp. and Penicillum sp. using
NMR-guided fractionation. Their structures were determined by
experimental/computed ECDcomparison.All compounds wereevaluated forantibacterial efectsand cytotoxicity.Notably,
compounds 1 and 5 showed weak cytotoxicity against MHCC-97H cels
ranging bioactivities， making them crucial for drug discovery
and biotechnology.12 Recent data reveal a striking predom-
inance of fungal-derived natural products over bacterial
counterparts,with the ratio increasing from 2.4:1 (2020） to
resources in natural product discovery.³ Nevertheless,conven-
tional laboratory cultivation methods often fail to mimic native
biosynthetic output of fungal SMs.4 Despite extensive
exploration of fungal SMs the field now contends with high
rediscovery rates of known compounds and diminishing
returns in identifying structurally novel bioactive molecules.5,6
Over the past decade, numerous innovative strategies have
emerged to activate silent biosynthetic pathways in fungi,
among which coculture techniques have proven particularly
effective for inducing novel metabolite production via genetic
regulatory mechanisms.7 Microbial coculture involves the
cultivation of two or more microbial strains within a shared,
controlled environment. Optimized coculture systems demon-
ance relative to conventional monoculture approaches.8
Currently，most coculture studies focus on strains from
organisms from the same or similar habitats remainsa
In previously published works,we described isolation and
identification of four new cyclic pentapeptides avellanins
from the mangrove-derived fungus Aspergillus sp. GXIMD
and a new cyclic heptapeptide cadophorin C
together with a known analogue cadophorin B from the
mangrove-derived Penicillium sp. GXIMD 03101.13 To better
explore their ability to produce structurally novel cyclic peptide
SMs,we investigated the SMs produced by their coculture.

employ two distinct patterns: linear and cross inoculation.14-18
